    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1864-01-04T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1864-01-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="511"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d511">
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                        Pruyn</persName>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 56.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic"
                                >Washington</hi>,</placeName>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1864-01-04">
                            <hi rend="italic">January</hi> 4, 1864.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of
                    your despatch of October 15, (No. 67.) The murder of the French lieutenant,
                    Camus, near <pb facs="0610" n="590" xml:id="pg_590"/> Kanagawa, as you have
                    described it, lends a new and shocking aggravation to the relations between
                    Japan and the western powers.</p>
                <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert H. Pruyn</hi>, Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c.,
                            &amp;c., &amp;c., Kanagawa.</hi>
                    </p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
